solution: Let $x = \log_\frac{1}{3}9$.  Then, we must have $\left(\frac{1}{3}\right)^x = 9$, so $x=\boxed{-2}$.
chatgpt_solution: We have $\left(\frac{1}{3}\right)^1 = \frac{1}{3}$, $\left(\frac{1}{3}\right)^2 = \frac{1}{9}$, and $\left(\frac{1}{3}\right)^3 = \frac{1}{27}$. Since $9$ is closer to $1$ than to $\frac{1}{3}$, we know that $2 < \log_\frac{1}{3}9 < 3$. We also know that $\left(\frac{1}{3}\right)^2 = \frac{1}{9}<9$, so $\log_\frac{1}{3}9>2$. Therefore, the value of $\log_\frac{1}{3}9$ must be $\boxed{\textbf{(C) }2\frac{1}{3}}$.
